# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-council-of-learned-societies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The **African Studies Association** (**ASA**) is a US-based association of scholars, students, practitioners, and institutions with an interest in the continent of Africa.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] Founded in 1957, the ASA is the leading organization of African Studies in North America, with a global membership of approximately 2000.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The association's headquarters are at Rutgers University in New Jersey.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The ASA holds annual conferences and virtual events for its members year-round.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The ASA Book Prize is given annually for the best scholarly work (including translations) on Africa published in English in the previous year and distributed in the United States.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The award was originally named after Melville Herskovits, one of the founders of the ASA.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The name was changed in 2019 as the ASA considered how to decolonize the discipline of African studies.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] Beginning in 1984, the association has awarded the Distinguished Africanist Award.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] Ogot Book Prize of the African Studies Association is awarded annually at the ASA Annual Meeting to the author of the best book on East African Studies published in the previous calendar year.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] Initiated in 2012, the award was made possible by a generous bequest from the estate of the late Professor Kennell Jackson, the award honors the eminent historian, Professor Bethwell A.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] In 2001, the ASA Board of Directors established an annual prize for the best graduate student paper.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The prize is awarded at the Annual Meeting for an essay presented at the previous year's Annual Meeting.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] This prize highlights exceptional scholarship produced by emerging scholars in any African studies related discipline.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The Conover-Porter Award is a biannual prize presented during 1980 - 2018 by the Africana Librarians Council of the African Studies Association (US) to reward outstanding achievement in Africana bibliography and reference tools.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] It honors two pioneers in African Studies bibliography, Helen F.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] Conover, of the Library of Congress, and Dorothy B.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] Presidents of the ASA are elected annually by the membership.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] Publications include *History in Africa: A Journal of Method*, published annually and *African Studies Review*, published quarterly.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The Association publishes a biannual newsletter *ASA News* for its members, and runs a news blog.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/african-studies-association] The African Heritage Studies Association was originally an offshoot of the African Studies Association, and was founded in 1968 by the ASA's Black Caucus and led by John Henrik Clarke.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The **American Academy of Religion** (**AAR**) is the world's largest association of scholars in the field of religious studies and related topics.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] It is a nonprofit member association, serving as a professional and learned society for scholars involved in the academic study of religion.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] It has some 10,000 members worldwide, with the largest concentration being in the United States and Canada.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR members are university and college professors, independent scholars, secondary teachers, clergy, seminarians, students, and interested lay-people.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR was founded in 1909 as the Association of Biblical Instructors in American Colleges and Secondary Schools.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The name was changed to National Association of Biblical Instructors (NABI) in 1933.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The American Academy of Religion was adopted as the organization name in 1963 to reflect its broader, inclusive mission to foster the academic study of all religions.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] Oxford University Press publishes *Journal of the American Academy of Religion* on behalf of the AAR.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] *Religious Studies News* is the quarterly newspaper of record for the organization; it transitioned from a print to online-only publication in 2010.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR also publishes *Reading Religion*, an online publication featuring book reviews by scholars in religious studies and other related fields.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR publishes five book series through Oxford University Press: Academy; Reflection and Theory in the Study of Religion; Religion, Culture, and Theory; Religion in Translation; and Teaching Religious Studies.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR presents awards each year to notable books in the study of religion.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] It offers three categories of Awards for Excellence: Analytical-Descriptive Studies, Historical Studies, and Constructive-Reflective Studies.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR hosts an annual meeting each year in November.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The AAR annual meeting is the world's largest meeting for religious studies scholars.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] Over 400 events, including meetings, receptions, and academic sessions, occur on the AAR program alone; hundreds more, hosted by affiliated societies and institutions, occur over the course of the meeting.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The location of the meeting changes each year.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The annual meetings of the AAR are attended by about half their membership "(some 4,500 in 2014), which make these meetings by far the most important social arena for academic interaction" in comparison with meetings of other North American academic societies for the study of religion.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The AAR annual meeting program is developed entirely by volunteers involved in program units representing disciplines and sub-disciplines within the field.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR offers activities on a regional level for its members.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] Professional development resources such as research grants, career services, and scholarships are some of the member benefits.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] AAR also advocates the importance of the critical study of religion on institutional and national levels.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-academy-of-religion] The president is part of the board of directors, which is elected by AAR members each September and takes up their post at the close of each annual meeting.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The **American Anthropological Association** (**AAA**) is an American organization of scholars and practitioners in the field of anthropology.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The AAA publishes more than 20 peer-reviewed scholarly journals, available in print and online through AnthroSource.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The first anthropological society in the US was the American Ethnological Society of New York, which was founded by Albert Gallatin and revived in 1899 by Franz Boas after a hiatus.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] 1879 saw the establishment of the Anthropological Society of Washington (which first published the journal *American Anthropologist*, before it became a national journal), and 1882 saw the American Association for the Advancement of Science established an anthropological section.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Boas and other anthropologist discussed the possibility of creating a single national society already in 1898, but fears that it might damage the AAAS caused a long discussion.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] In 1901 the AES and ASW sent members to attend the meeting of the AAAS anthropologists in Chicago in which discussions continued and there was general agreement that a national society should be formed.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Boas advocated a restricted membership of 40 "professional anthropologists", but the AAA's first president, W.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] McGee, ensured that membership would be open to everyone with an interest in the discipline.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] At its incorporation, it assumed responsibility for the journal*American Anthropologist*, created in 1888 by the Anthropological Society of Washington (ASW).
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Business affairs are conducted by a 41-member Section Assembly representing each of the association's constituent sections, and a 15-member Executive Board.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] From an initial membership of 175, the AAA grew slowly during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Annual meetings were held primarily in the Northeast and accommodated all attendees in a single room.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The offices of the AAA are located in Arlington, Virginia.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The AAA is composed of 40 sections, which are groups organized around identity affiliations or intellectual interests within the discipline of anthropology.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Sections each have an elected president or chair; many publish journals and host meetings.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The AAA publishes more than 20 section publications including *American Anthropologist*, *American Ethnologist*, *Cultural Anthropology*, *Anthropology & Education Quarterly* and *Medical Anthropology Quarterly*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The AAA's official magazine, *Anthropology News*, is published bimonthly.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] AAA publications are available online through AnthroSource.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Since 2007, journals have been published in partnership with Wiley-Blackwell since 2007.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Since 1962 the association has published the AAA AnthroGuide, giving staff and program information about anthropology departments.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Other issues addressed from the 1970s through the 1980s included illegal antiquities trade, the insertion of religious beliefs into social science texts, the preservation of endangered nonhuman primates, and the religious significance of peyote to Native Americans.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] In 2004, in response to President George W.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Bush's call for a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage, the Association issued a statement on marriage and the family.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The Association also has adopted resolutions against the 2003 invasion of Iraq, against the use of anthropological knowledge as an element for physical or psychological torture, and against any covert or overt U.S. military action against Iran.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Following a referendum in 2023, the Association endorsed a boycott of Israeli academic institutions, joining the BDS movement.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] A number of ideologically polarized debates within the discipline of anthropology have prompted the association to conduct investigations.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] These include the dispute between Derek Freeman and defenders of Margaret Mead, as well as the controversy over the book *Darkness in El Dorado*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The AAA has issued a number of statements on the topic of race, and since the 1950s has argued publicly that race is best understood as a cultural or bio-cultural rather than mostly biological construction.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] In 2006, the association developed and continues to manage a public education program titled "RACE: Are We So Different?" The program includes a traveling museum exhibit, an interactive website, and educational materials.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Initially, AAA was highly skeptical of the concept of universal human rights, with some anthropologists arguing that because of cultural relativism there are no principles that can be universally valid for humans of all cultures.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] IN 1947 the AAA issued a statement on Human rights, noting that value judgments are culturally contextual and arguing that a declaration about universal human rights ought to take into consideration and encompass all the different human value systems.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] This stance has gradually been abandoned by most anthropologists, many of whom today see universal human rights as an important way through which discrimination and oppression of cultural minorities can be reduced.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] District Court in Arizona entered a permanent injunction barring enforcement of the remaining provisions.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] With the law's repeal, AAA's ban on considering AAA conferences in Arizona was lifted.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Through 2007 and 2008, debates surrounding anthropologists and the military resurfaced in response to the Pentagon's Human Terrain System (HTS) project.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Following a number of national news articles on the project, anthropologists began to debate the project and related ethical issues.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Proponents of the program argued that anthropologists were providing much-needed cultural knowledge about local populations and helping to decrease violence in their areas of operation.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Critics, however, argued that HTS anthropologists could not receive informed consent from their research subjects in a war zone and that information provided by anthropologists might put populations in danger.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] To address these issues, the Association's Executive Board released a statement on 31 October 2007.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] It cited "sufficiently troubling and urgent ethical issues" raised by the project, including the difficulties for HTS anthropologists to receive informed consent without coercion from their research subjects and to uphold their ethical mandate to "do no harm" to those they study.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] The AAA urged members to adhere to its code of ethics, which outlines principles and guidelines for ethical behavior.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] However, the association does not adjudicate cases involving charges of unethical behavior or bar members from participating in the HTS program.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] In addition, the Association's Commission on the Engagement of Anthropology with US Security and Intelligence Communities (CEAUSSIC) issued a final report released during the AAA's 2007 annual meeting, based on over a year of work.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] It neither endorsed nor condemned anthropological work with military, intelligence and security organizations, but instead outlined the opportunities and challenges of working in these sectors.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Opposition to military cooperation was evident during that meeting.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Some critics of the HTS program have suggested that scholars who perform classified work with the military be expelled from the organization.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] During an event organized by the Network of Concerned Anthropologists, a graduate student who had recently been expelled from the HTS program spoke out about her experiences.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] She argued that the program was poorly run but was doing positive work in helping military officers with "nation-building" activities.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Until August 2007, AnthroSource was a collaboration between the University of California Press and the Association.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] It, along with all their journals, has since been removed from the University of California Press by the AAA Board and transferred to Wiley-Blackwell.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] Commencing 2008, AnthroSource was to be hosted and managed by Wiley-Blackwell as part of the five-year publishing contract awarded.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-anthropological-association] AAA presidents have been drawn from all of the four subdisciplines of American anthropology: Until 2003 the presidents counted 46 socio-cultural anthropologists, 19 archeologists, six physical anthropologists and six linguists.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] The American Association for Italian Studies (AAIS) was founded in 1988.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] Its purpose is to encourage, support, and conduct research activities in Italian culture, including areas such as Italian language, art, music, history, literature, folklore, and popular culture, and well as its influence on other cultures.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] The AAIS holds an annual meeting and periodically publishes a scholarly journal called *Italian Culture*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] The Association for the Study of Modern Italy was founded in 1982 by Christopher Seton-Watson, to bring together individuals and organisations from the UK and abroad with teaching, research, professional or general interests in modern Italy from all disciplinary angles.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] Today, ASMI's membership is international and includes scholars and others from a wide range of disciplinary backgrounds including history, political science, languages, geography, literature and anthropology.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] ASMI publishes a quarterly journal called *Modern Italy*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] The Canadian Association for Italian Studies (CAIS, formerly known as the Canadian Society for Italian Studies or CSIS) was established in 1972, to foster and advance Italian studies in Canada and in the larger global community.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] The CAIS aim is to provide a forum for the exchange of ideas through the presentation and discussion of papers that deal with diverse aspects of Italian language, literature, pedagogy, society, and culture.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] The CAIS publishes a biannual journal called *Quaderni d’italianistica*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] It also publishes a bi-annual journal called *Italian Studies*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] API publishes a bi-annual journal called *Italian Studies in Southern Africa / Studi d’Italianistica nell’Africa Australe* (ISSA).
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] The *Journal of Modern Italian Studies* (*JMIS*) is one of the leading English language forums for debate and discussion on modern Italy.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-italian-studies] This peer-reviewed journal publishes five issues a year, each containing scholarly articles, book reviews and review essays relating to the political, economic, cultural, and social history of modern Italy from 1700 to the present.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-the-history-of-medicine] The **American Association for the History of Medicine** is an American professional association dedicated to the study of medical history.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-the-history-of-medicine] The AAHM is the largest society dedicated to medical history in the United States, and the oldest such organization in North America.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-the-history-of-medicine] The American Association for the History of Medicine was established in 1925 as the American Section of the International Society for the History of Medicine.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-the-history-of-medicine] The first president of the association was Fielding Hudson Garrison.Its current membership surpasses 1,000 people.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-the-history-of-medicine] The AAHM publishes a quarterly journal titled the *Bulletin of the History of Medicine*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-the-history-of-medicine] Its current membership surpasses 1,000 people.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-association-for-the-history-of-medicine] The AAHM awards the Genevieve Miller Lifetime Achievement Award annually since 1988, when it was then known as the AAHM Lifetime Achievement Award.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The **American Council of Learned Societies** (**ACLS**) is a private, nonprofit federation of 75 scholarly organizations in the humanities and related social sciences founded in 1919.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The federation was created in 1919 to represent the United States in the Union Académique Internationale (International Union of Academies).
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The founders of ACLS, representatives of 13 learned societies, believed that a federation of scholarly organizations (dedicated to excellence in research, and most with open membership) was the best combination of U.S. democracy and intellectual aspirations.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] According to the council's constitution, its mission was advancing humanistic studies and social sciences and maintaining and strengthening national societies dedicated to those studies.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Since its founding, ACLS has provided the humanities and related social sciences with leadership, opportunities for innovation, and national and international representation.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The council's many activities have at their core the practice of scholarly self-governance.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Central to ACLS throughout its history have been its programs of fellowships and grants aiding research.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] ACLS made its first grants, totaling $4,500, in 1926; in 2012, ACLS awarded over $15 million in fellowship stipends and other awards to more than 320 scholars in the United States and abroad.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] All ACLS awards are made through rigorous peer review by specially appointed committees of scholars from throughout the United States and, in some programs, abroad.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] During the late 1950s, the council encouraged Hans Wehr in his writing of the first English edition of his *Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic* (1962).
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The executive directors of the ACLS member societies meet in a Conference of Administrative Officers (CAO); before 1988, this was the Conference of Secretaries.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] At its first meeting in 1925 the conference had 11 members, including Frederic Ogg of the American Political Science Association and Ernest Burgess of the American Sociological Society (now the American Sociological Association).
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In addition to peer review, the ACLS has organized committees to research promising fields of study.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The concept of organizing expertise around a cultural region grew out of the council's early work in Far Eastern and Slavic studies.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] After World War II, when the practical need for such competence was evident, the ACLS and the Social Science Research Council developed African, Asian, Latin American, Near and Middle Eastern, Slavic, and East and West European studies.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1927 the ACLS Committee on Research in Native American Languages, under the leadership of Franz Boas and Edward Sapir, began in 1927 to "secure an adequate record of Indian languages and dialects." The Committee on a Journal of Medieval Studies, begun in 1924, founded the journal *Speculum*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The Committee on the History of Ideas, which included Richard McKeon and Arthur Oncken Lovejoy, created the *Journal of the History of Ideas*.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Since the introduction of new research technology, the ACLS has helped scholars explore the impact of new technologies on their fields.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1964 the council developed a grant and fellowship program to encourage computer use in humanistic research, which continues in its Digital Innovation Fellowships.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] *Our Cultural Commonwealth*, the 2006 report by the ACLS Commission on Cyberinfrastructure for the Humanities and Social Sciences, recommended digital humanities using new forms of research, reading and writing.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS has an interest in the problems of scholarly publication and has conducted a survey of publication needs, established a publication service to advise scholars on communicating research and aided scholars with subsidies and publication.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS-sponsored National Enquiry into the Production and Dissemination of Scholarly Knowledge investigated all aspects of the dissemination of humanistic scholarship from 1974 to 1979.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1979 it presented a report, *Scholarly Communication: The Report of the National Enquiry*, published by the Johns Hopkins University Press and operated its Office of Scholarly Communication and Technology in Washington, D.C. until 1984.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Today, the ACLS Humanities E-Book collection focuses on how digital innovations can enhance scholarly communication.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] By bringing scholars together as scholars rather than as specialists, the ACLS advocates for the humanities in public forums and policy arenas.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The council's role in establishing (in 1964) and reauthorizing (in 1985) the National Endowment for the Humanities is an example.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] While continuing to represent the U.S. in the *Union Académique Internationale*, the ACLS has participated in international scholarly exchange.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] From 1961 to 1992, its American Studies Program aided overseas scholars specializing in the study of the U.S.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The council and other members of the Associated Board of Research Councils founded the Council for International Exchange of Scholars, which administers the graduating-senior Fulbright Program.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1992 the United States Information Agency asked the ACLS to reinstitute the Fulbright Program in Vietnam, operated by the U.S.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS Center for Educational Exchange with Vietnam offers fellowship and study opportunities to Vietnamese scholars.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1966 the ACLS, the Social Science Research Council and the National Academy of Sciences founded the Committee on Scholarly Communication with China, which maintains an office in Beijing to assist American schools with programs in that country.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS has extended its support of research to scholars in the former USSR through the ACLS Humanities Program in Belarus, Russia and Ukraine, and in Africa through its African Humanities Program.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In June 1999 under its President John D'Arms, ACLS received a $3-million, 5-year grant from The Andrew W.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Mellon Foundation to initiate The History E-Book Project.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In October 1999, Eileen Gardiner and Ronald G.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Musto of Italica Press became the project directors working in collaboration with the Scholarly Publishing Office of the University of Michigan Library and with New York University Press.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Three years later and two years ahead of schedule, on September 1, 2002, the History E-Book Project website launched online with over 500 titles.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] These had been reviewed and recommended by historians and scholarly societies and were often award-winning books in different area specialties.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] "HEB continued to grow and to adjust accordingly, becoming self-sufficient in 2005, garnering attention and a supportive constituency among scholars, presses, libraries, and learned societies." HEB mission expanded to include all the humanities disciplines and was renamed ACLS Humanities E-Book.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] At the end of 2019, ACLS transferred the management and administration of Humanities E-Book to the University of Michigan, where this online collection of over 5,400 books of high quality in the humanities and related social sciences is accessible through institutional subscription.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS' organizational structure has experienced few major changes during the council's existence.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Most notable is the growth in the number of member societies, from 13 to 71.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] As the number of societies increased, it became impossible for a council with two representatives of each member to govern effectively.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] In 1947 a council-elected board of directors was created, and the number of delegates from each society was reduced to one.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Another change occurred in 1957; the council moved its headquarters from Washington to New York and appointed Frederick Burkhardt its first president, signaling a new determination to place scholarship at the center of public culture.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS was incorporated in the District of Columbia in 1924, receiving a congressional charter in 1982.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] For the fiscal year ending June 30, 2017, the ACLS reported an endowment of US$120 million.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] During the same period the institution distributed about US$15.9 million in grants and fellowships.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] The ACLS archives are in the Manuscript Division of the Library of Congress.
[src:american-council-of-learned-societies/american-council-of-learned-societies] Graves Awards in the Humanities or Arnold L.
